Roger, pre-flight checklist and platform alignment.
Report when ready.

60 seconds to launch.
30 seconds to launch.

Roll program.

Roger, circularization burn scheduled for the next Ap passing, in about {{timeToAp}}.
Prepare for the burn using the Circularize Orbit checklist, and get into a circular orbit.

When ready and the orbit is circular and aligned to 28.91 degrees inclination, call the REQUEST RENDEZVOUS BURN radio command.
Follow the rendezvous checklist and get on a rendezvous trajectory with Agena.
We are {{timeToTransferBurn}} from the initial transfer burn. Ensure you are in SEF attitude, burn will be in prograde direction.
One minute. Let's get it as precise as earlier.
MARK, zero the IVIs! [Press ROGER when burn is complete.]
When ready, set the radar to standby.
Warming up the radar. Let me know when it's ready.

This will automatically lock on Agena if in range. We will arrive in {{timeToAp}}.

Uplinking the final rendezvous burn, standby.

BURN, zero the IVIs. Press READY when done.
Set computer to RNDZ, start it when ready.
While the OBC module is loading, change the FDAI1 source to RDR, and the FDAI1 Display to ATT. Follow the FDAI pointer to point towards the target.
Keep it centered in the window and reference the radar for thrust planning. Move closer to Agena.

Turn on the DOCKING lights and turn of the ACQ. when ready.
Roger, will do. Maneuvering towards Agena.
Really good. Align with Agena and perform the docking.
We have docking!
Great job. And hello Agena!
Excellent job! Complete the post-docking checklist, then take a break. This completes our primary objective, congratulations with the first docking in history. Another well deserved first for you!
That puts me in the lead again, right?
That is correct {{profileName}}, score is now 7 - 6. We are moving out of range, see you in about 10 minutes.
Ok, excellent job. We finally made it!
Yeah, great job, it takes two to do the job. We will soon take a break and then fire up that Agena engine. Can't wait to see Earth from record breaking altitudes!
Exactly, planned orbit is at an altitude of about 755 nmi. The highest Earth orbit ever reached by a crewed spacecraft. Verify OAMS is off and control mode is set to FREE.
Ok, OAMS going off.
And the platform to Free.
Ok, OAMS are off and platform is set to Free.
Ok, it seems we are building some roll!?
Yes. Is OAMS closed and shut off?
OAMS controller power is off, and same with the OAMS propellant valve. It can't be us.

Roger. 400 and done.
Roger, let's use our OAMS to reduce the roll. Enabling OAMS and setting control mode to Direct.
It must be an issue with Agena. Keep stabilizing the roll as good as you can. Press the emergency release when ready and back away from Agena when undocked.
Undocking.
Undocked!
{{capsuleName}}, Com Check. How do you read?

We're rolling up and we can't turn anything off.
Continuously increasing in a left roll.
We are trying to correct the rates.
Ok, we have regained control.
That's great news, excellent recover. Bring the craft home as soon as possible.

Ok, lets plan an entry with a splashdown in the Atlantic. Our retrograde burn should be on the west coast of the U.S. Again, using the Orbital Cursor on Orbit View (F3), drag the slider so its position is above the coast.
Then get back into the cockpit view, and request that our retrograde burn should happen on the orbital cursor point. Press DONE! when ready.
We should now have a retrograde burn time. Start the PRE RETRO checklist now and follow the steps.
We are 5 minutes from retrograde burn. Proceed with the 256 seconds to retro checklist to prepare for the retrograde burn using the RUN feature.
Going through the checklist now.
Checklist complete.
Adapter is separated.
Ok, complete the 1 minute to retro checklist to retrograde burn using the RUN feature.
Retro sequence starting.
Thrusting. Continue the checklist. Burn lasts 20 seconds.
Retros jettisoned, complete the POST-RETRO JETTISON checklist.
We are getting ready for atmospheric entry.
Verify D-Ring.
Preparing for entry.
Roger. Good luck.
Going through the atmosphere.
{{capsuleName}}, do you read?

Follow the landing checklist and prepare for drogue release.
Roger! Great to see you, that was a close call.
Roger, sure was, I think it was a matter of seconds. Waiting for drogue.

Roger.

Roger.

Great!
Preparing for recovery.
Roger, welcome home. The first docking mission in history. Unfortunately, it didn't go as planned, but at least it's a docking, with a safe landing. We are all OK.
That is correct. I'll guess you will complete the job?
You bet, have to tie our scores you know, it will be 7-7 if all goes well. I also heard that if successful, it will be the last Gemini mission before Apollo.
Yes, and this was my last Gemini flight. It sure is a great craft and a huge achievement.
It certainly is. I look forward to my next flight, and to progressing into the Apollo program.
Unfortunate with all the issues surrounding it, but it is a beautiful craft.
I'm sure we will sort out the issues before flight, and there's unmanned tests planned.
Indeed. I will see you at the debrief. (Transmission ends, mission complete)

Title: LET'S DOCK!?
Description: The Agena Target Vehicle has launched into orbit. You will re-try docking, and if successful, use the Agena engine to raise your orbit to 755 nmi altitude, before returning home. If successful, this will be the first docking in history, and the longest distance humans has been from Earth. The Block I Command Module spacecraft is also rapidly making progress in the Apollo project, meaning we are slowly getting closer to the Moon.
BriefingText:
Agena is in a 160 x 160 nmi circular orbit with inclination 28.91 degrees.

This mission has 3 main goals:

1) Rendezvous & Docking
You will be launched in-plane with Agena and need to circulate and rendezvous with it, before station keeping and docking.

2) Raise Orbital Altitude at Ap
Once docked, you will use the Agena engine to raise your orbit to about 755 nmi altitude.

3) Safely return home

Good luck!
